{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. Here, the Court is not satisfied that the mere existence of the University\rquote s control over the Foundation, or the existence of University personnel on the Foundation Board, creates an \u8220\'3fomnipresent danger\u8221\'3f that the University, acting in it position of control may be acting primarily in its own interests, and not those of the Foundation. Of course the Court recognizes that furtherance of the Foundation\rquote s mission inherently benefits the University, and therefore, any action of the purportedly \u8220\'3finterested\u8221\'3f fiduciaries, including the University, in approving a transaction or undertaking a course of action could be considered to \u8220\'3fprimarily benefit\u8221\'3f the University. At the same time, however, so long as the course of action taken by the fiduciaries is consistent with the Foundation\rquote s mission, the Foundation benefits to an equal degree. In such instances, it can hardly be said that the University receives a benefit to the exclusion and detriment of the Foundation. This is precisely why the 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Sinclair Oil, supra,
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 model works much better in the context of the corporate structure under scrutiny in the present litigation than that of the reasoning set forth in 
}
