{\b1 \qc \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb400 
DEFENDANTS\rquote  MOTION FOR PARTIAL SUMMARY JUDGMENT ON THE \u8220\'3fSOLE BENEFICIARY\u8221\'3f ISSUE
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
This matter arises from a verified complaint filed on July 17, 2002 by Plaintiffs, William Robertson (\u8220\'3fMr. Robertson\u8221\'3f), Robert Halligan (\u8220\'3fMr. Halligan\u8221\'3f), Anne R. Meier, and Katherine Ernst (collectively \u8220\'3fPlaintiffs\u8221\'3f); against Defendants, Shirley M. Tilghman, John J.F. Sherrerd; Peter Wendell, and Stephen Oxman (collectively the \u8220\'3fUniversity-designated Trustees\u8221\'3f), Princeton University (the \u8220\'3fUniversity\u8221\'3f). (collectively \u8220\'3fDefendants\u8221\'3f), and the Robertson Foundation (the \u8220\'3fFoundation\u8221\'3f). Plaintiffs filed an amended verified complaint on November 12, 2004. On December 22, 2004, Defendants filed their answer and affirmative defenses. By way of the present motion, Defendants seek partial summary judgment that the University is the \u8220\'3fsole beneficiary\u8221\'3f entitled to receive distributions from the Foundation, and therefore, granting them. declaratory relief on their first counterclaim and dismissing those portions of Count Eight of Plaintiffs\rquote  amended verified complaint, as well as Plaintiffs\rquote  first prayer for relief.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Briefly, the present motion is rooted in Defendants\rquote  position that the plain language of the Foundation\rquote s Certificate of Incorporation requires that the University remain the sole tax-exempt charity supported by the Foundation. Therefore, Defendants assert that Plaintiffs requests to have the Foundation\rquote s Certificate of Incorporation amended or reformed to eliminate the University\rquote s right to designate a majority of the Foundation\rquote s Board, strip the Foundation of its current classification as a supporting organization of the University, and convert the Foundation into a private foundation-free from University control or involvement-would be both contrary to the clear and unambiguous language of the Foundation\rquote s Certificate of Incorporation and contrary to controlling legal principles.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
By contrast, Plaintiffs contend that nothing in the Foundation\rquote s Certificate of Incorporation, the relevant evidence or the applicable law bestow \u8220\'3fsole beneficiary\u8221\'3f status upon the University. Instead, Plaintiffs contend that the University is simply the agent or instrument utilized by the Foundation-to-fulfill -its purported charitable purpose of recruiting, training and placing career government employees, particularly in the federal government in the area of international relations. Plaintiffs submit that this Court has the equitable power to fashion whatever relief it may ultimately deem appropriate, and should therefore, not preclude certain types of relief at this juncture. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Plaintiffs submit that such equitable powers include the Court\rquote s applying the doctrines of cy pres and deviation if the Court ultimately finds that the University is no longer an appropriate steward for carrying out the donors\rquote  charitable goals.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In and around 1960, Marie Robertson (\u8220\'3fMs. Robertson\u8221\'3f), an heir of the founder of the Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Company (\u8220\'3fA&P\u8221\'3f), decided to donate 700,000 shares of A&P stock to Princeton University. (Cert. of Douglas S. Eakeley, Exh. \u8220\'3f1\u8221\'3f.) On March 20, 1961, the Foundation was formally incorporated in the State of Delaware. (
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Id.
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 at \u8220\'3f2\u8221\'3f.) As specified in the Foundation\rquote s Certificate of Incorporation, the Foundation was created to further the following purposes and objectives:
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
This corporation is organized and shall.be operated exclusively for charitable, scientific, literary, or educational purposes and for no other purpose. In furtherance of such purposes its objective is to strengthen the Government of the United States and increase its ability and determination to defend and extend freedom throughout the world by improving the facilities for the training and education of men and women for government service and to contribute, lend, pay over, or assign the income of the corporation and/or the funds or property of the corporation (any payments of principal being subject to the limitation of article 11(c) hereof) to or for the use of Princeton University for any one or more or all of the following uses:
\par 
}
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
(a) To establish or maintain and support at Princeton University, and as part of the Woodrow Wilson School, a Graduate School where men and women dedicated to public service may prepare themselves for careers in government service with particular emphasis on the education of such persons for careers in those areas of the Federal Government that are concerned with international relations and affairs;
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
(b) To establish or maintain scholarships or fellowships, which will provide full, or partial support to students admitted to such Graduate School, whether such students are candidates for degrees, special students, or part-time students;
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
(c) To provide collateral and auxiliary services, plans and programs in furtherance of the object and purpose above set forth, including but without limitation, internship programs, plans for public service assignments of faculty or administrative personnel, mid-career study help, and programs for foreign students or officials training.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
