Initially, the Court finds it necessary to briefly discuss what Defendants exactly mean by the use of the term \u8220\'3fsole beneficiary\u8221\'3f, as it appears that Plaintiffs may misinterpret Defendants\rquote  use of the term. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Plaintiffs contend that the Defendants\rquote  use of the term \u8220\'3fsole beneficiary\u8221\'3f contradicts Defendants\rquote  position throughout the present litigation, in that Defendants are adamant that corporate law must govern in the present matter; but seek to apply a private trust concept in the context of the present motion. Additionally, Plaintiffs contend that treating the University as the \u8220\'3fsole beneficiary\u8221\'3f would require the Court to ignore almost all of the language of Article 3. of the Foundation\rquote s Certificate of Incorporation, which Plaintiffs submit clearly evidences the donors\rquote  intent that the United States and the Federal Government be the true beneficiaries of the Foundation.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Based on Defendants\rquote  response to Plaintiffs\rquote  contention, it would appear that Plaintiffs misconstrue, understandably, Defendants\rquote  use of the term. Defendants maintain that they do not use the term \u8220\'3fsole beneficiary\u8221\'3f for purposes of supporting an assertion that the University is the sole beneficiary of a formal trust, or to suggest that the University\rquote s students and the public are not also beneficiaries of the Foundation. (
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
See
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Defendants\rquote  Opposition Brief Re Business Judgment Rule, at 7 n.3.) Instead, Defendants insist that the use of the term \u8220\'3fsole beneficiary\u8221\'3f is used as a general term to describe their argument that the Foundation\rquote s Certificate of Incorporation only authorizes the Foundation to contribute funds \u8220\'3fto or for the use of Princeton University\u8221\'3f for the purposes set forth therein. Therefore, in the context of the present motion, the Court\rquote s use of the term \u8220\'3fsole beneficiary\u8221\'3f is used to refer to Defendants\rquote  position that under the Foundation\rquote s Certificate of Incorporation, Foundation assets may only be used \u8220\'3fto or for the use of\u8221\'3f the University in carrying out the Foundation\rquote s purpose and objectives.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
As already stated in the Court\rquote s Statement of Reasons attached to its June 20, 2003 Order, and its Statement of Reasons attached to its Order on Defendants\rquote  motion for partial summary judgment on the Article 11 (c) issue, the laws of the State of Delaware apply in interpreting the language of the Foundation\rquote s Certificate of Incorporation. The parties are in agreement that courts typically apply general contract principles when interpreting certificates of incorporation. 
}
