Despite the Court\rquote s broad and equitable powers to fashion an appropriate remedy, the Court must also address whether, consistent with such powers, the Court could order the application of the equitable doctrines of cy pres and deviation, in the event that the Court were not inclined to sever the relationship between the Foundation and the University, or strip the University of its power to designate a majority of the Foundation Board. Essentially, the dispute concerns whether, despite the Court\rquote s broad equitable powers; it could even- resort to these equitable-doctrines, as Defendants assert that they are only available in the context of a charitable trust, not a charitable corporation. According to Defendants, principles of trust law should not be interjected into the present dispute, as the donors made a conscious decision to form a corporate entity, and therefore, must accept the application of Delaware corporate law. By contrast, Plaintiffs contend that the equitable doctrines of cy pres or deviation are applicable to the present matter because the various restricted gifts from the Foundation to the University are in the form of a charitable trust.
