Clearly, the University-designated Trustees are fiduciaries. Similarly, as stated in the Court\rquote s Statement of Reasons Re Business Judgment Rule, the University is a fiduciary, in a limited sense. While the Court does not find the University to be a fiduciary simply in its role as beneficiary or sole means to carrying out the overarching purpose of the Foundation, the Court did find that the University has a limited fiduciary role in its appointing University-designated Trustees and, more importantly in its role of delegating to the University Treasurer\rquote s Office the responsibility of calculating the annual settlement. In short, the University may well be a hybrid, part beneficiary-part fiduciary. It remains to be seen whether the University\rquote s actions in its role as a fiduciary warrant removal of the University in its role as a beneficiary or sole means to carrying out the Foundation\rquote s overall purpose.
